Yes, both are known MSTest v4 behavioral changes (not bugs):

**1. Tests appear as new in Azure DevOps** â€” The `TestCase.Id` generation algorithm changed to fix long-standing bugs. There's no code fix; your test history will re-baseline from this point forward.

**2. `TestContext.TestName` in `[ClassInitialize]`** â€” v4 now enforces lifecycle scope. `TestName` is per-test context and isn't available during class-level initialization. Move that access to `[TestInitialize]` or into individual test methods.

**Other behavioral changes to watch for:**

| Symptom | Cause | Fix |
|---|---|---|
| Tests not discovered / discovery failures | `TreatDiscoveryWarningsAsErrors` now defaults to `true` | Fix warnings or set to `false` in `.runsettings` |
| Tests hang that didn't before | AppDomain disabled by default | Set `DisableAppDomain` to `false` in `.runsettings` |
| `vstest.console` finds zero tests (MSTest.Sdk) | MSTest.Sdk defaults to MTP mode | Add `Microsoft.NET.Test.Sdk` or use `dotnet test` |
| New analyzer warnings | Several analyzers upgraded from Info â†’ Warning | Fix or suppress in `.editorconfig` |

For the `TestContext.TestName` fix specifically:

```csharp
// Before â€” throws in v4
[ClassInitialize]
public static void Init(TestContext ctx)
{
    var name = ctx.TestName; // âťŚ throws
}

// After â€” move to TestInitialize
[TestInitialize]
public void Setup()
{
    var name = TestContext.TestName; // âś… works here
}
```
